abstract: The test to get into New York’s elite public schools has led to debate over school segregation. So how much weight does the test have and what are the proposed changes?
snippet: The test to get into New York’s elite public schools has led to debate over school segregation. So how much weight does the test have and what are the proposed changes?
lead_paragraph: Since Mayor Bill de Blasio proposed changing how students are admitted to eight of the city’s most elite public high schools on June 3, the Specialized High Schools Admissions Test, or SHSAT, has been subject to intense public debate.

abstract: David Oscar helped start an L.G.B.T. & Allies meeting at a group home in the Bronx because “I felt that the world in general was against who I was.”
snippet: David Oscar helped start an L.G.B.T. & Allies meeting at a group home in the Bronx because “I felt that the world in general was against who I was.”
lead_paragraph: RIVERDALE, N.Y. — At the start of a recent meeting of the L.G.B.T. & Allies group at the Hebrew Home here, the group leaders Olivia Cohen and Liisa Murray reminded attendees of the ground rules, which they had written on a poster board.

headline_main: Border Children, North Korea, Global Trade: Your Thursday Briefing

abstract: New York City filed two lawsuits on Wednesday accusing a broker and landlords of not renting apartments to people who receive rental assistance.
snippet: New York City filed two lawsuits on Wednesday accusing a broker and landlords of not renting apartments to people who receive rental assistance.
lead_paragraph: For the past four years, New York City has tried to persuade landlords and real estate brokers to rent apartments to low-income people and homeless people with bonuses and pledges that rent would be guaranteed with government vouchers.
